Inspection of single dataset

The example data is actigraphy data of a dyad with one client and their partner. The data was sampled with 1 Hz in 60-second epochs. Participants have different measurement coverage.

The clients epochs start at 2016-11-22 17:03:00 and end at 2016-11-30 17:52:00. The time series spans 9 days, including 9 ACTIVE periods, 8 REST periods and 8 SLEEP periods. The dataset contains 11570 observations, 11240 complete observations with data in all variables, 05:30:00 hours are not covered (2.85%). 14 periods of at least 1 minute have missing observations in one or more variables.

The partners epochs start later, at 2016-11-22 17:10:00 and end at 2016-11-30 17:52:00. The time series spans 9 days, including 9 ACTIVE periods, 8 REST periods and 8 SLEEP periods. The dataset contains 11567 observations, 10446 complete observations with data in all variables, 18:41:00 hours are not covered (9.69%). 15 periods of at least 1 minute have missing observations in one or more variables.

Investigations of time periods where one or more variables are missing suggest, failure to records stems from taking of the device, e.g.for showering in the morning, forgetting to put the device on again (several hours missing), or technical failures (several minutes missing).

Smoothing

Figure 1. White light exposure, log scaled.

Visual inspection of the time course of white light exposure with different time bins suggests that bin of 20 and even more 30 minutes may capture relevant variation best while smoothing over noisy variation. Smaller bins (e.g.5 or 10 minutes) heavily depend on occasional extreme values, while larger bins (e.g.60 minutes) flatten regional changes that may still be of interest. Thus, further analysis is based on 30-minute bins.

Regularity light exposure and activity

Regularity of light exposure and activity across the time of data collection be examined visually.

Visually, autocorrelations for activity do not differ between client and partner. Activity, as the only endogenous variable, clearly shows a regular circadian rhythm. For the other exogenous variables, white light, red light, blue light, and green light, autocorrelations are less pronounced for the client compared to the partner. Only autocorrelations of red light reveal disrupted circadian rhythm for the client but not for the partner. Quantitatively, the maximum of autocorrelations in a window between 12 and 36 hours are around 24 hours for both, client and partner, and thus do not suggest any deviation from circadian rhythm (see below). For detailed quantitative evaluation of regularity and periodicity, other statistical means may be employed, such as time frequency analysis.

Correlation of light exposure and activity

To analyze the relationship between light exposure and activity, cross correlations were computed to examine irregularities in their relationship across time.

Strikingly, there are small deflections of the clients cross-correlations between activity and the all distinct wave lengths (red light, green light, blue light). This coincides with spikes of light exposure with small spikes in the clients light exposure that occur between around 2:00:00 and 6:30:00 (cf.Figure 2). Yet, these deflections may coincide with periods of missing values in the morning listed that may bias for the activity estimate for respective bins (cf.Table 1).

Exploratory analysis

On single dyad

A single dyad consisting of one client with chronic insomnia and their partner is used as example for analysis of the sleep status depending on time, light exposure and partner activity.

Possible approaches/ hypotheses

When looking at 30-minute bins, sleep status over time most likely depends on diagnosis of insomnia. First, one may suspect that particularly in the insomnia patient, i.e.the client, light of specific wave lengths may enhance the probability of waking up. Second, insomnia patients may easily be woken up be movement by their bed-partners.

Variables

The primary outcome measure, probability of waking up is measured by the fraction of wakefulness during the selected minute span, here 30 minutes. Note, that categorization of sleep status (asleep or awake) is based on temporally consistent activity. Sleep status changes when the participant is at least 10 minutes immobile or mobile, thus sleep status and activity measure are correlated and concurrent, and activity is not considered a meaningful predictor. Predictors of interest are measurement of red light, green light, blue light, and white light. Additionally, movement of bed partners can be quantified by partner-activity during sleep periods of the client. Distribution of those variables are log-normal and can be transformed to normal distribution. However, there are high rates of missing values in all variables (red light: 94.1%, green light: 94.6%, blue light: 94.1%, white light: 95.4%, partner-activity: NA%). Therefore, all variables are included in their in their original form.

Model setup and estimation

In order to quantify difference between client and patient, its suggested to use one model. A model was fitted with data from client and patient entered a grouping vector group, a transformed night time vector, as well as a red, green, blue, and white light values in their original form into the model. An interaction term for the group and any other variable was modeled to capture the differential reaction of client and partner to light and partner activity.

Further considerations

However, further aspects that needs to be considered, in confirmatory hypothesis testing, e.g.correlation of subsequent bins, and that each day represents a repeated measurement of the same construct, sleep disturbance. One approach to account for the repeated measurement nature is to model data in a hierarchical fashion, e.g.using linear mixed models. Yet, because of the scarcity of above zero values in predictor variables, there are to few observations per day, which precludes to model clustering in days. Accordingly, estimation procedures yield singularity warnings.

Future analyses may incorporate the complete dataset in their analysis. During model setup, one should consider clustering of the data on different levels: observations are clustered within participants, and participants are clustered in dyads with their respective partners and within diagnosis group (client or partner). Using the full data set, the influence of light exposure and activity of the individual during wake hours on sleep periods and sleep disturbance could be investigated by using the aggregated data on actie and sleep periods provided by the summaries in the raw dataset. For the analysis, simplifying assumptions could be made, such as that sleep periods do not influence each other.
